Saprolmycins A–E are anti-Saprolegnia parasitica antibiotics. To identify the gene cluster for sapro- lmycin biosynthesis in Streptomyces sp. TK08046, polymerase chain reaction using aromatase and cyclase gene-speciﬁc primers was performed; the spr gene cluster, which codes for angucycline biosynthe- sis, was obtained from the strain. The cluster con- sists of 36 open reading frames, including minimal polyketide aromatase, cyclase, oxygenase, and deoxy sugar biosynthetic genes, as deﬁned by homology to the corresponding the urdamycin, Sch-47554, and grin- genes of camycin biosynthetic gene clusters in Streptomyces fradiae, Streptomyces sp. SCC-2136, and Strepto- myces lusitanus, respectively. To establish the func- tion of the gene cluster, an expression cosmid vector containing all 36 open reading frames was intro- duced into Streptomyces lividans TK23. The trans- formant was conﬁrmed to express the biosynthetic genes and produce saprolmycins by liquid chro- matography–mass the extract. Angucycline antibiotics comprise a large group of aromatic polyketides of microbial origin.1,2) These compounds exhibit a wide range of biological activi- ties, including antibacterial, antiviral, and antitumor activities, and are produced by type-II polyketide syn- thases. All angucycline class antibiotics contain a tetra- cyclic benz[a]anthraquinone skeleton of decaketide origin. The structural diversity of these compounds is very broad, reﬂecting variations in oxidation states and sugar moieties. The reaction mixture consisted of 1 × GoTaq Green Master Mix (Promega, Madison, WI, USA), 2 μM of each primer, DNA isolation and manipulation. and 0.5 ng/μl of genomic DNA. After heating at 95 °C for 4 min, PCR was performed for 30 cycles (95 °C 1 min, 50 °C 30 s, 72 °C 45 s). After puriﬁcation with the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit (QIAGEN, Hilden, Germany), the PCR products were linked with pMD20 Vector (TaKaRa) by using a DNA ligation Kit. E. coli was transformed with the plasmid DNA and selected clones were used for sequencing analysis. Cloning of a gene cluster for saprolmycin biosynthe- sis. A cosmid library was constructed from the sapro- lmycin producer. Streptomyces sp. TK08046 genomic DNA was partially digested with Sau3AI and ligated to the pKU465cos cosmid vector. The transformants were cultivated at 30°C for 5 days on a rotary shaker in 500-ml Sakaguchi ﬂasks containing 150 ml of a medium con- sisting of soluble starch 2.0%, glucose 0.5%, yeast extract (Difco, Detroit, MI, USA) 0.5%, bacto peptone (Difco) 0.3%, meat extract 0.3%, KH2PO4 0.02%, MgSO4.7H2O 0.06%, and kanamycin 50 μg/ml (pH 7.2 before sterilization). The resulting fermentation broth (150 ml) was centrifuged and the supernatant was extracted with ethyl acetate (150 ml × 2). Homology search showed that 19 of the ORFs were homologous to angucycline biosynthetic genes (Table 1). Based on their positions and deduced functions, 27 ORFs were designated spr genes and presumed to comprise a gene cluster for angucycline biosynthesis in Streptomyces sp. TK08046. The spr gene cluster contained genes encoding putative ketosynthase, chain length determinant factor (CLF), acyl carrier protein, ketoreductase, aromatase, cyclase, oxygenase, and deoxy-sugar biosynthetic proteins. Fur- thermore, (sprR1, sprR2, and sprR3) and two putative transporter genes (sprJ and spr5) were found in the gene cluster. Expression of the spr gene cluster in S. lividans To establish the function of the spr gene cluster, the expression cosmid pKU-SPR (which contains the clus- ter) was introduced into S. lividans TK23. A strain of S. lividans TK23 harboring the empty cosmid vector pKU465cos was used as a control. The transformant bearing pKU-SPR (or the control) was cultivated and an extract of the supernatant was analyzed by HPLC. S. lividans expressing the spr genes produced sapro- lmycins A, C, and E, but neither saprolmycins B nor D (Fig. 3). Pseudomolecular ions of saprolmycin A, C, and E were observed at m/z 705 [M-H]-, 705 [M-H]-, 819 [M-H]-, respectively, by mass spectrometric analy- sis (Supplementary Fig. 5). These results conﬁrmed that the spr gene cluster is responsible for saprolmycin biosynthesis in Streptomyces sp. TK08046.

A 44-kb DNA fragment containing aromatase and cyclase genes was sequenced and found to comprise a saprolmycin biosynthetic gene cluster in Streptomyces sp. TK08046. The cluster includes genes encoding a minimal polyketide synthase (ketosynthase, CLF, and acyl carrier protein), a ketoreductase, an aromatase, and a cyclase, proteins that are commonly encoded in angucycline biosynthetic gene clusters. By analogy to other angucyclines, the saprolmycin condensation reac- tion is catalyzed by a minimal polyketide synthase con- sisting of SprD, SprE, and SprC. Phylogenetic analysis of SprE, which is homologous to CLF, revealed that SprE of saprolmycin, GcnI of grincamycin, and UrdB of urdamycin are closely related with a short genetic distance, as shown in Supplementary Fig. 6. In addi- tion, the analysis suggested that SprE is involved in the formation of the polyketide chain length (C20). SprG is a putative ketoreductase and is encoded within the aro- matic PKS gene subcluster. sprH shows homology to a gene encoding an aromatase, an activity that plays an important role in the formation of the ﬁrst aromatic ring in angucycline biosynthesis.9) SprH is similar to UrdL and SchP4 proteins that are involved in urdamy- cin and Sch-47554 biosyntheses, respectively. SprC is also similar to UrdF and SchP9, which are putative cyclases catalyzing the ring formation of angucycline. SprI resembles UrdM, which is a putative oxygenase- reductase based on BLAST alignments. UrdM consists of two regions, including an N-temimal ﬂavin-depen- dent oxygenase domain and a C-terminal reductase domain. It has been suggested that UrdM hydroxylates at C-12b by a Baeyer–Villiger oxygenation reaction in the course of urdamycin biosynthesis.13,14) Therefore, SprI is presumed to hydroxylate at C-12b in

It has been suggested that UrdM hydroxylates at C-12b by a Baeyer–Villiger oxygenation reaction in the course of urdamycin biosynthesis.13,14) Therefore, SprI is presumed to hydroxylate at C-12b in sapro- lmycin biosynthesis (Fig. 4). SprB also resembles UrdE, which has been proposed to serve as an oxygenase that catalyzes oxygenation at C-12 and C-12b in the aromatic ring.3,13) Thus, SprB may

catalyze oxygenation at C-12 in saprolmycin biosynthe- sis, as shown in Fig. 4. Three putative glycosyltrans- ferases are encoded within the spr gene cluster. Based on the structure of saprolmycins, these glycosyltrans- ferases presumably transfer three different deoxysugar moieties, D-olivose, L-rhodinose, and L-aculose. SprGT3 shows similarity to the glycosyltransferase GcnG3 and the C-glycosyltransferase SchS7. Multiple alignment of SprGT1-3 with other glycosyl- transferases revealed a consensus motif (Supplementary Fig. 2–4). In addition, this multiple alignment showed a highly conserved region containing two histidine resi- dues in glycosyltransferases. This analysis suggested that the histidine residue could play an important role in the catalytic activity of the enzyme; indeed, histidine residues have been shown to serve as important active sites of substrate binding.16) Three proteins encoded by the spr gene cluster (SprA, SprQ, and SprZ) show homology to uncharacterized proteins. Although, the functions of SprA, SprQ, and SprZ are not deﬁned, we speculate that these proteins are involved in sapro- lmycin biosynthesis. S. lividans expressing the spr genes produced sapro- lmycins A, C, and E. However, the saprolmycin pro- ducer Streptomyces sp. TK08046 and the transformant bearing pKU-SPR (which contains the spr gene cluster) showed different saprolmycin production (Fig. 3). This difference is likely due to differences in culture conditions and growth rates between Strepto- myces sp. TK08046 and S. lividans.

In summary, we identiﬁed a gene cluster, cloned from Streptomyces sp. TK08046, that is responsible for the biosynthesis of saprolmycin. The function of the gene cluster was conﬁrmed by heterologous gene expression in S. lividans. Further studies on the biosyn- thesis of saprolmycin are in progress. We expect that the saprolmycin and other genetic engineering of angucycline biosynthetic clusters will permit the cre- ation of novel angucyclines in the future.
